### Plant cell organelles that perform photosynthesis and store starch

### Plant cells with visible [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts)

Oh, you want to talk about plastids. Fine. These rather industrious [membrane-bound organelles](/Membrane-bound_organelle) are consistently found nestled within the [cells](/Cell_(biology)) of [plants](/Plants), [algae](/Algae), and, for those with a discerning eye for biological minutiae, certain other [eukaryotic](/Eukaryotic) organisms. Don't mistake them for mere cellular components; plastids are, in essence, domesticated [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiotic) [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) that, at some point approximately 1.5 billion years ago, decided to integrate rather than freeload, fundamentally reshaping the trajectory of life on Earth. [[1]](#cite_note-1) It’s a classic tale of assimilation, truly.

Among the various specialized forms these organelles assume, you'll encounter the ubiquitous [chloroplasts](/Chloroplast), the verdant engines of [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis). Then there are the more aesthetically inclined [chromoplasts](/Chromoplast), dedicated to the sophisticated synthesis and meticulous storage of various pigments, because even cells appreciate a vibrant hue. Not to be overlooked are the [leucoplasts](/Leucoplast), a collection of non-pigmented plastids, some of which possess the remarkable capacity to [differentiate](/Cellular_differentiation) into other specialized variants as cellular needs dictate. And, for the truly specialized, or perhaps one might say, the evolutionarily adventurous, there are the [apicoplasts](/Apicoplast), non-photosynthetic relics found within the notoriously parasitic [apicomplexa](/Apicomplexa), derived from a secondary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) event. They’ve clearly moved beyond the quaint practice of sunbathing.

The foundational primary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiotic) event, a pivotal moment in cellular evolution, is estimated to have transpired roughly 1.5 billion years ago. This monumental integration occurred within the lineage of the [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida)—a clade encompassing all [land plants](/Embryophyte), [red algae](/Red_algae), [green algae](/Green_algae), and the somewhat less celebrated [glaucophytes](/Glaucophyte). The initial symbiont was likely a [cyanobiont](/Cyanobiont), a type of symbiotic [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) with genetic ties to the genus [Gloeomargarita](/Gloeomargarita_lithophora). [[2]](#cite_note-Moore_et_al_2019-2)[[3]](#cite_note-de_Vries_Gould_2018-3) As if one such profound event weren't enough, another distinct primary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) occurred much later, approximately 140 to 90 million years ago, involving the photosynthetic plastids found in [Paulinella](/Paulinella) [amoeboids](/Amoeboid). This particular event saw the integration of [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) from the genera [Prochlorococcus](/Prochlorococcus) and [Synechococcus](/Synechococcus), collectively known as the "PS-clade." [[4]](#cite_note-Marin_et_al_2007-4)[[5]](#cite_note-Ochoa_de_Alda_et_al_2014-5) The evolutionary narrative doesn't stop there, of course. [Secondary and tertiary endosymbiosis](/Chloroplast) events have subsequently unfolded across a vast array of organisms, leading to an even greater diversity of plastid forms and functions. Some organisms have even developed the somewhat opportunistic, if not outright thieving, capacity to sequester ingested plastids from their prey—a transient process elegantly termed [kleptoplasty](/Kleptoplasty).

It was [A. F. W. Schimper](/Andreas_Franz_Wilhelm_Schimper) [[6]](#cite_note-6)[[a]](#cite_note-7) who, with commendable clarity, first provided a formal name, detailed description, and precise definition for these organelles. Plastids, as we now understand them, harbor their own distinct [double-stranded DNA](/DNA) molecule. For a considerable time, this DNA was presumed to be exclusively circular, mirroring the [circular chromosome](/Circular_prokaryote_chromosome) characteristic of prokaryotic cells. However, recent findings suggest that this assumption might be, shall we say, a touch simplistic, with evidence pointing towards a more nuanced, potentially even ["..a linear shape"](/Chloroplast_DNA) in certain contexts. These organelles are not just energy converters; they are sophisticated biochemical factories, serving as crucial sites for the manufacturing and storage of pigments and a host of other vital chemical compounds indispensable to the [autotrophic](/Autotroph) [eukaryotes](/Eukaryote) they inhabit. Many plastids contain [biological pigments](/Biological_pigments), such as those directly involved in [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) or those that simply dictate a cell's color, adding a splash of visual information to the cellular landscape. Even in organisms that have, perhaps regrettably, forfeited their photosynthetic capabilities, plastids remain highly useful, particularly for the synthesis of complex molecules like the [isoprenoids](/Terpenoid). [[8]](#cite_note-Picozoans-8)

### In land plants

#### Plastid types
**[Leucoplasts](/Leucoplast) in plant cells.**

#### Chloroplasts, proplastids, and differentiation

In the realm of [land plants](/Embryophyte), the plastids that deign to contain [chlorophyll](/Chlorophyll) are the primary architects of [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis). They masterfully convert external [sunlight energy](/Light_energy) into internal chemical energy, simultaneously drawing carbon from the Earth's atmosphere and, in a rather generous gesture, enriching it with the very oxygen that sustains most complex life. These are, as you might have surmised, the [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts), easily identifiable by their characteristic green hue (see top graphic).

Beyond their role as photosynthetic powerhouses, other plastids are engaged in the intricate synthesis of [fatty acids](/Fatty_acids) and [terpenes](/Terpenes). These compounds can either be directly utilized for energy production or serve as essential raw materials for the construction of myriad other complex molecules. For instance, the plastids residing in [epidermal cells](/Epidermal_cells) are responsible for fabricating the constituent components of the [plant cuticle](/Plant_cuticle)—that protective outer layer—including its [epicuticular wax]. This entire process often begins with [palmitic acid](/Palmitic_acid), which itself is initially synthesized within the [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) of the underlying [mesophyll tissue](/Mesophyll_tissue). Furthermore, plastids are adept at storing diverse cellular reserves, including vital [starches](/Starch), [fats](/Fat), and [proteins](/Protein). [[9]](#cite_note-Kolattukudy-9)

Every plastid traces its lineage back to [proplastids](/Proplastid) (sometimes referred to as proplasts [[10]](#cite_note-Azevedo_et_al_2008-10)), which are typically found in the [meristematic](/Meristem) regions of a plant, those zones of active growth and division. These foundational [proplastids](/Proplastid), along with nascent [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts), commonly propagate through [binary fission](/Binary_fission). Interestingly, even more mature [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) retain this capacity for division, ensuring the continued proliferation of these essential organelles.

The undifferentiated nature of plant [proplastids](/Proplastid) allows them to undergo remarkable [differentiation](/Cellular_differentiation), transforming into various specialized forms tailored to specific cellular functions (refer to the top graphic for a visual representation). They are capable of developing into any of the following distinct variants: [[11]](#cite_note-Wise_2006-11)

*   **[Chloroplasts](/Chloroplast):** The quintessential green plastids, primarily responsible for the execution of [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis).
*   **[Etioplasts](/Etioplast):** These are essentially precursor [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts), typically found in plants grown in darkness. They await light exposure to mature and initiate photosynthetic activity.
*   **[Chromoplasts](/Chromoplast):** As their name suggests, these are the brightly colored plastids, specializing in the synthesis and storage of various pigments, contributing to the vibrant hues of flowers and fruits.
*   **[Gerontoplasts](/Gerontoplast):** These plastids assume control during [plant senescence](/Plant_senescence), orchestrating the systematic dismantling of the photosynthetic apparatus as a plant ages and prepares for dormancy or death.
*   **[Leucoplasts](/Leucoplast):** These are colorless plastids, primarily involved in the synthesis of [monoterpenes](/Terpene) and other non-pigmented compounds.

From the broad category of [leucoplasts](/Leucoplast) emerge even more finely specialized plastids, each with a distinct storage function:

*   The [aleuroplasts](/Leucoplasts), for instance.
*   **[Amyloplasts](/Amyloplast):** These are dedicated to storing substantial quantities of [starch](/Starch). Beyond mere storage, they play a critical role in detecting [gravity](/Gravity), a function essential for maintaining [geotropism](/Gravitropism), ensuring that roots grow downwards and shoots upwards.
*   **[Elaioplasts](/Elaioplast):** Specializing in the accumulation and storage of [fats](/Fat) and oils.
*   **[Proteinoplasts](/Proteinoplast):** These plastids are involved in the storage and, in some cases, modification of [protein](/Protein).
*   Or the less commonly known **[Tannosomes](/Tannosome):** These are responsible for synthesizing and producing [tannins](/Tannin) and various [polyphenols](/Polyphenols), compounds often involved in plant defense and coloration.

The plasticity of these organelles is quite remarkable; depending on their evolving morphology and the specific functional demands of the cell, plastids possess the inherent ability to both [differentiate](/Cellular_differentiation) and redifferentiate between these various forms, adapting to the dynamic needs of the plant.

#### Plastomes and Chloroplast DNA/ RNA; plastid DNA and plastid nucleoids

Each plastid, in its quiet efficiency, meticulously maintains multiple copies of its own distinct genetic blueprint, a unique genome referred to as a [plastome](/Plastome) (a portmanteau derived from 'plastid genome'). In the case of a [chlorophyll](/Chlorophyll) plastid, or [chloroplast](/Chloroplast), this is more specifically termed a 'chloroplast genome' or, perhaps more commonly, 'chloroplast DNA'. [[12]](#cite_note-Wicke_et_al_2011-12)[[13]](#cite_note-Wicke_Naumann_2018-13) The precise number of genome copies within each plastid is not static; it exhibits considerable variability. In rapidly dividing, youthful cells, which might only contain a handful of plastids, the copy number can soar to 1000 or even more. Conversely, in mature cells, which typically house numerous plastids, this number can drop to 100 or fewer.

A [plastome](/Plastome) is typically a comprehensive [genome](/Genome) that encodes crucial transfer [ribonucleic acids](/Ribonucleic_acid) ([tRNA](/TRNA)s) and ribosomal [ribonucleic acids](/Ribonucleic_acid) ([rRNAs](/RRNA)). It also holds the genetic instructions for proteins directly involved in [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) and the intricate processes of plastid gene [transcription](/Transcription_(genetics)) and [translation](/Translation_(biology)). However, it's vital to recognize that these plastid-encoded proteins constitute only a meager fraction of the total protein complement necessary to construct and maintain *any* given type of plastid. The vast majority of plastid proteins are, in fact, encoded by [nuclear](/Cell_nucleus) genes residing within the plant cell's nucleus. Consequently, the expression of both nuclear and plastid genes is meticulously co-regulated, a sophisticated coordination act ensuring the harmonious development and [differentiation](/Cell_differentiation) of plastids.

Many plastids, particularly those indispensable for [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis), are characterized by numerous internal membrane layers, forming an elaborate internal architecture. Within this complex environment, plastid [DNA](/DNA) doesn't just float freely; it exists as intricate protein-DNA complexes. These complexes are strategically associated with localized regions within the plastid's inner envelope [membrane](/Inner_nuclear_membrane) and are aptly named 'plastid [nucleoids](/Nucleoid)'. Unlike the highly organized nucleus of a [eukaryotic](/Eukaryotic) cell, a plastid [nucleoid](/Nucleoid) is notably *not* enveloped by its own nuclear membrane. Each [nucleoid](/Nucleoid) region may contain a surprising density of genetic material, often holding more than 10 copies of the plastid [DNA](/DNA).

Consider the journey from an undifferentiated [proplastid](/Proplastid) to a specialized plastid: a [proplastid](/Proplastid) typically harbors a solitary [nucleoid](/Nucleoid) region, usually situated near its center. As this [proplastid](/Proplastid) embarks on its developmental or differentiating path, the developing plastid acquires multiple [nucleoids](/Nucleoid), which then migrate and become localized at the periphery of the organelle, firmly bound to the inner envelope membrane. Throughout this entire process of [differentiation](/Cellular_differentiation)—from [proplastids](/Proplastid) to [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts), and indeed when plastids transition from one specialized type to another—these [nucleoids](/Nucleoid) undergo significant transformations in their morphology, overall size, and precise location within the organelle. This dynamic remodeling of plastid [nucleoids](/Nucleoid) is largely believed to be orchestrated by meticulous modifications to both the abundance and the specific composition of the proteins associated with the [nucleoids](/Nucleoid) themselves.

In typical [plant cells](/Plant_cell), one might observe the occasional formation of long, slender protuberances, rather charmingly termed [stromules](/Stromule). These delicate extensions emanate from the main body of the plastid, reaching out into the surrounding cell [cytosol](/Cytosol), sometimes even forming intricate interconnections between several plastids. This network allows for the efficient movement of proteins and smaller molecules both within and through these [stromules](/Stromule). Curiously, in a laboratory setting, most cultured cells—which tend to be considerably larger than their natural counterparts—exhibit a propensity for producing exceptionally long and abundant [stromules](/Stromule) that often extend all the way to the cell periphery, a testament to their inherent adaptability or perhaps just a quirk of artificial environments.

A rather intriguing piece of evidence emerged in 2014, suggesting the potential, albeit controversial, loss of the plastid [genome](/Genome) in *[Rafflesia](/Rafflesia) lagascae*, a non-photosynthetic [parasitic](/Parasitism) flowering plant, and in *[Polytomella](/Polytomella)*, a genus of non-photosynthetic [green algae](/Green_algae). Despite extensive and diligent searches for plastid genes in both of these [taxons](/Taxon), no definitive results were yielded. However, the conclusive assertion that their [plastomes](/Plastome) are entirely absent remains a subject of ongoing scientific debate. [[14]](#cite_note-14) Some scientists, with a healthy dose of skepticism, argue that a complete loss of the plastid [genome](/Genome) is highly improbable. Even these non-photosynthetic plastids, they contend, typically retain essential genes required to complete various crucial [biosynthetic pathways](/Biosynthesis), including, for example, the intricate process of heme biosynthesis. [[14]](#cite_note-14)[[15]](#cite_note-Barbrook_et_al_2006-15)

Even in the hypothetical scenario of a complete plastid [genome](/Genome) loss within [Rafflesiaceae](/Rafflesiaceae), the plastids themselves are still present, albeit as "shells" devoid of [DNA](/DNA) content. [[16]](#cite_note-DNA_of_Giant_Corpse_Flower_Parasite_Surprises_Biologists-16) This structural persistence, despite genetic emptiness, bears an unsettling resemblance to the enigmatic [hydrogenosomes](/Hydrogenosome) found in various organisms, raising further questions about the minimal requirements for organelle maintenance.

### In algae and protists

The diversity of plastids extends significantly beyond land plants, encompassing a fascinating array of types within [algae](/Algae) and [protists](/Protist):

*   **[Chloroplasts](/Chloroplast):** These are, of course, found in [green algae](/Green_algae) (the evolutionary progenitors of plants) and in other organisms that have, through various evolutionary pathways, derived their [genomes](/Genome) from green algae.
*   **[Muroplasts](/Glaucophyte):** Also known by the more descriptive terms cyanoplasts or cyanelles, these are the distinctive plastids of [glaucophyte](/Glaucophyte) algae. They bear a striking resemblance to plant [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts), with one critical difference: they possess a [peptidoglycan](/Peptidoglycan) [cell wall](/Cell_wall) that is remarkably similar in composition to that found in [bacteria](/Bacteria), a clear echo of their ancient cyanobacterial origins.
*   **[Rhodoplasts](/Red_algae):** These are the vibrant red plastids characteristic of [red algae](/Red_algae). Their unique pigmentation allows them to photosynthesize efficiently even at extraordinary marine depths, reportedly down to 268 meters. [[11]](#cite_note-Wise_2006-11) A key distinction between the [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) of plants and [rhodoplasts](/Rhodoplasts) lies in their starch metabolism: plant [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) synthesize and store starch as granules *within* the plastids. In contrast, [red algae](/Red_algae) synthesize [floridean starch](/Floridean_starch), but this is stored *outside* the plastids, specifically in the [cytosol](/Cytosol). [[17]](#cite_note-Viola_et_al_2001-17)
*   **[Secondary and tertiary plastids](/Chloroplast):** These represent a more complex evolutionary history, originating from subsequent [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) events involving the engulfment of either [green algae](/Green_algae) or [red algae](/Red_algae) by other eukaryotic cells.
*   **[Leucoplast](/Leucoplast):** In the context of [algae](/Algae), this term is broadly applied to all unpigmented plastids. Their precise functions, however, can diverge significantly from those of the [leucoplasts](/Leucoplast) found in plants.
*   **[Apicoplast](/Apicoplast):** These are the non-photosynthetic plastids found in the [Apicomplexa](/Apicomplexa), a phylum of [obligate parasitic](/Obligate_parasite) organisms. Their presence is a result of secondary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis), a testament to a photosynthetic past now repurposed for parasitic survival.

The plastid found in photosynthetic *[Paulinella](/Paulinella)* species is often referred to as a 'cyanelle' or chromatophore, diligently serving its role in [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis). [[18]](#cite_note-Lhee_et_al_2019-18)[[19]](#cite_note-Gabr_et_al_2020-19) What makes this particular plastid noteworthy is its origin from a much more recent [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiosis) event, estimated to have occurred within the last 140–90 million years. This represents a rare and distinct second primary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) of [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria), entirely independent of the ancient event that gave rise to the [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida). [[20]](#cite_note-Sánchez-Baracaldo_et_al_2017-20)[[21]](#cite_note-Delaye_et_al_2016-21)

It's worth noting that certain plastid types, specifically [etioplasts](/Etioplast), [amyloplasts](/Amyloplast), and [chromoplasts](/Chromoplast), are considered plant-specific and are generally not observed in [algae](/Algae). [[citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)] Furthermore, plastids in [algae](/Algae) and [hornworts](/Hornwort) can also exhibit structural differences from typical plant plastids, notably by containing specialized structures known as [pyrenoids](/Pyrenoid). [[22]](#cite_note-Robison_2025-22)

### Inheritance

In the grand scheme of biological reproduction, most plants exhibit a rather strict uniparental inheritance pattern for their plastids, meaning these organelles are typically passed down from only one parent. Generally speaking, [angiosperms](/Angiosperms) (flowering plants) primarily inherit their plastids from the female [gamete](/Gamete). In contrast, many [gymnosperms](/Gymnosperms) (conifers and their relatives) often receive their plastids from the male [pollen](/Pollen). Similarly, [algae](/Algae) also adhere to this uniparental inheritance, ensuring that the plastid [DNA](/DNA) from the other parent is, for all intents and purposes, completely lost from the lineage.

Under normal circumstances, particularly in intraspecific crossings—those resulting in typical hybrids within the same species—the inheritance of plastid [DNA](/DNA) appears to be rigorously uniparental, almost exclusively stemming from the female line. However, when it comes to interspecific hybridizations, the inheritance pattern becomes, shall we say, considerably more erratic and less predictable. While plastids are still predominantly inherited from the female parent in these interspecific crosses, there exists a notable body of reports detailing instances where hybrids of flowering plants have demonstrably inherited plastids from the male parent. Furthermore, approximately 20% of [angiosperms](/Angiosperms), including commercially significant species like [alfalfa](/Alfalfa) (*Medicago sativa*), naturally exhibit a biparental inheritance pattern for their plastids, making them a fascinating exception to the rule. [[23]](#cite_note-Zhang_2010-23)

### DNA damage and repair

The delicate [DNA](/DNA) within the plastids of [maize](/Maize) seedlings is not immune to the ravages of time and environment; it demonstrably accumulates increasing amounts of damage as the seedlings progress through their developmental stages. [[24]](#cite_note-Kumar_et_al_2014-24) This damage is predominantly attributed to the pervasive oxidative environments generated by [photo-oxidative reactions](/Photo-oxidation_of_polymers) and the energetic, yet potentially destructive, processes of [photosynthetic](/Photosynthesis) and [respiratory electron transfer](/Electron_transport_chain). While some of these damaged [DNA](/DNA) molecules are meticulously [repaired](/DNA_repair) by cellular machinery, any [DNA](/DNA) that harbors unrepaired damage is, rather unsentimentally, degraded into non-functional fragments, ensuring cellular integrity.

Crucially, the essential [DNA repair](/DNA_repair) proteins are not encoded by the plastid's own [genome](/Genome); instead, they are encoded by the cell's [nuclear genome](/Nuclear_genome). Once synthesized, these proteins are then painstakingly translocated into the plastids, where they perform their vital duty of maintaining [genome](/Genome) stability and integrity by diligently repairing the plastid's [DNA](/DNA). [[25]](#cite_note-Oldenburg_Bendich_2015-25) A compelling example of this intricate cooperation can be observed in the [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) of the moss *[Physcomitrella patens](/Physcomitrella_patens)*. Here, a protein involved in [DNA mismatch repair](/DNA_repair) (Msh1) actively interacts with other proteins crucial for [recombinational repair](/DNA_repair) ([RecA](/RecA) and RecG). This collaborative effort is fundamental to preserving the stability of the plastid [genome](/Genome), a testament to the complex, multi-layered strategies cells employ to safeguard their genetic information. [[26]](#cite_note-Odahara_et_al_2017-26)

### Origin

Plastids, as we've already established with a sigh of cosmic weariness, are widely considered to be the venerable descendants of ancient [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiosis) [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria). The primary [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiosis) event that initiated the lineage of the [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida) is hypothesized to have occurred a staggering 1.5 billion years ago [[27]](#cite_note-Ochoa_de_Alda_et_al_2014-27). This singular, transformative event bestowed upon early [eukaryotes](/Eukaryote) the remarkable capacity to perform [oxygenic photosynthesis](/Carbon_fixation), forever altering the atmospheric composition and paving the way for the evolution of complex life. [[28]](#cite_note-Hedges_et_al_2004-28) Since that primordial integration, three distinct evolutionary lineages have emerged within the [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida), each characterized by uniquely named plastids: the familiar [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) in [green algae](/Green_algae) and [plants](/Plants), the vibrant [rhodoplasts](/Rhodoplast) in [red algae](/Red_algae), and the distinctive [muroplasts](/Muroplast) found in the [glaucophytes](/Glaucophyte). These plastids are not merely differentiated by name; they exhibit significant variations in their specific pigmentation and their intricate ultrastructure. For instance, [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) in [plants](/Plants) and [green algae](/Green_algae) have, over evolutionary time, shed all their [phycobilisomes](/Phycobilisomes)—the efficient [light harvesting complexes](/Light_harvesting_complex) that are still present in [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria), [red algae](/Red_algae), and [glaucophytes](/Glaucophyte). Instead, plant [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) developed the complex internal structures of [stroma](/Stroma_(fluid)) and grana [thylakoids](/Thylakoid). The [glaucocystophycean plastid](/Glaucophyte), in stark contrast to [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts) and [rhodoplasts](/Rhodoplasts), still retains the discernible vestiges of its ancestral cyanobacterial [cell wall](/Cell_wall), a living fossil of its prokaryotic past. All of these primary plastids, irrespective of their specific lineage, are consistently enveloped by two membranes, a tell-tale sign of their ancient [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiosis) origin.

As previously touched upon, the plastid within photosynthetic *[Paulinella](/Paulinella)* species, often referred to as a 'cyanelle' or chromatophore, represents a comparatively recent and entirely separate [endosymbiotic](/Endosymbiosis) event, occurring approximately 90–140 million years ago. [[18]](#cite_note-Lhee_et_al_2019-18)[[19]](#cite_note-Gabr_et_al_2020-19) This makes it the *only* other known instance of a primary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) event involving [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) outside of the venerable [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida). Intriguingly, this particular plastid belongs to the "PS-clade" (comprising [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) genera like [Prochlorococcus](/Prochlorococcus) and [Synechococcus](/Synecoccus)), which constitutes a distinct sister clade to the [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) that gave rise to the plastids within the [Archaeplastida](/Archaeplastida). [[4]](#cite_note-Marin_et_al_2007-4)[[5]](#cite_note-Ochoa_de_Alda_et_al_2014-5)

In stark contrast to these primary plastids, which arose directly from the single [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) of a prokaryotic [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria), the more intricate 'complex plastids' have a more convoluted origin story. They emerged through 'secondary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis)', a process where a [eukaryotic](/Eukaryote) organism, having already acquired a primary plastid, then proceeded to engulf *another* [eukaryotic](/Eukaryote) organism that *itself* contained a primary plastid. [[29]](#cite_note-Chan_Bhattachary_2010-29) When a [eukaryote](/Eukaryote) successfully engulfs either a [red](/Red_algae) or a [green alga](/Green_algae) and manages to retain the algal plastid, that secondary plastid is typically, and rather tellingly, surrounded by more than two membranes—a ghost of its multiple ancestral engulfments. In some instances, these complex plastids may experience a reduction in their metabolic and/or photosynthetic capabilities, adapting to their new host environment. Examples of [algae](/Algae) harboring complex plastids derived from the secondary [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis) of a [red alga](/Red_algae) include the [heterokonts](/Heterokont), [haptophytes](/Haptophyte), [cryptomonads](/Cryptomonads), and the majority of [dinoflagellates](/Dinoflagellate) (these are often referred to as [rhodoplasts](/Red_algae)). Conversely, those that chose to [endosymbiose](/Endosymbiosis) a [green alga](/Green_algae) include the [euglenids](/Euglenid) and [chlorarachniophytes](/Chlorarachniophyte) (housing [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts)). The [Apicomplexa](/Apicomplexa), a phylum of [obligate parasitic](/Obligate_parasite) [alveolates](/Alveolates) that includes the causative agents of devastating diseases such as [malaria](/Malaria) (*[Plasmodium](/Plasmodium)* spp.) and [toxoplasmosis](/Toxoplasmosis) (*[Toxoplasma gondii](/Toxoplasma_gondii)*), along with numerous other human and animal afflictions, also harbor a complex plastid. While this organelle has been lost in some [apicomplexans](/Apicomplexa) (e.g., *[Cryptosporidium parvum](/Cryptosporidium_parvum)*, which causes [cryptosporidiosis](/Cryptosporidiosis)), the '[apicoplast](/Apicoplast)' is no longer capable of [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis). Yet, it remains an absolutely essential organelle for the parasite's survival, making it a highly promising [target](/Drug_target) for the development of novel [antiparasitic drugs](/Antiparasitic_drug). A rather poetic twist, considering its photosynthetic ancestry.

And then there are the true opportunists: some [dinoflagellates](/Dinoflagellates) and certain [sea slugs](/Sea_slug), particularly those belonging to the genus *[Elysia](/Elysia_(gastropod))*. These organisms engage in a rather audacious practice: they consume [algae](/Algae) as food but, instead of fully digesting them, they selectively retain the plastids from their meals. The purpose? To temporarily benefit from the [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) performed by these stolen organelles. After a period of exploitation, the plastids are, with characteristic efficiency, eventually digested as well. This fascinating, if somewhat predatory, process is aptly termed [kleptoplasty](/Kleptoplasty), a name derived from the Greek *kleptes* (κλέπτης), meaning "thief."

### Plastid development cycle

**An illustration of the stages of inter-conversion in plastids**

In 1977, J.M. Whatley, with a clarity that belied the complexity of the subject, proposed a plastid development cycle that challenged earlier, more linear views. Whatley's insightful model posited that plastid development is far from being a simple, unidirectional progression. Instead, it is a remarkably intricate and cyclic process, allowing for considerable flexibility and interconversion between different plastid forms. At the heart of this cycle are the [proplastids](/Proplastid), which serve as the fundamental precursor stage for all the more differentiated forms of plastids, as elegantly depicted in the accompanying diagram to the right. [[30]](#cite_note-Whatley_1978-30) This dynamic model underscores the adaptability of plastids, enabling them to respond to changing environmental conditions and cellular demands by transforming from one specialized state to another and, in many cases, back again.

